{
  "local_port": 56760,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How many 3-digit numbers can be formed using only 2, 3, 4, 7 and 8 with no repeats?",
  "response": "To determine how many 3-digit numbers can be formed using the digits 2, 3, 4, 7, and 8 without any repetitions, we will select 3 digits from the available 5 digits and then arrange these 3 digits.\n\n1. **Selection of digits**: \n   We are choosing 3 digits from the 5 digits available (2, 3, 4, 7, 8). The number of ways to choose 3 digits from 5 can be calculated using the combination formula:\n\n   \\[\n   \\binom{n}{r} = \\frac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}\n   \\]\n   where \\( n \\) is the total number of items to choose from, and \\( r \\) is the number of items to choose.\n\n   Here, we have \\( n = 5 \\) and \\( r = 3 \\):\n\n   \\[\n   \\binom{5}{3} = \\frac{5!}{3!(5-3)!} = \\frac{5!}{3! \\cdot 2!} = \\frac{5 \\times 4}{2 \\times 1} = 10\n   \\]\n\n   Therefore, there are 10 ways to choose 3 digits from the set.\n\n2. **Arrangement of chosen digits**: \n   Next, we need to arrange the 3 digits we have chosen. The number of ways to arrange 3 digits is given by the factorial of the number of digits, which is \\( 3! \\) (3 factorial):\n\n   \\[\n   3! = 3 \\times 2 \\times 1 = 6\n   \\]\n\n3. **Total number of 3-digit numbers**: \n   Now we multiply the number of ways to choose the digits by the number of arrangements of those digits:\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{Total} = \\text{Number of choices} \\times \\text{Number of arrangements} = 10 \\times 6 = 60\n   \\]\n\nThus, the total number of 3-digit numbers that can be formed using the digits 2, 3, 4, 7, and 8, without repeating any digit, is \n\n\\[\n\\boxed{60}.\n\\]",
